      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2085ceb874302e32",
      "text": "Luhmann hypothesizes that once social systems are personified, they gain considerable advantages in their environmental positions. Latour sees personification as a secular opportunity to expand the pool of potential candidates who can actively participate in the political ecology. These are important insights, but [[Gunther Teubner]] wants to highlight another aspect. In encounters with nonhuman entities, their personification proves to be one of the most effective strategies for dealing with uncertainty. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "907d83282a86f848",
      "text": "Personification transforms a subject-object relationship into an ego-alter relationship. To this extent, although it also does not generate certainty about Alter from Ego's point of view, it enables Ego to act in situations where Alter is opaque. When Ego treats an object \"as if\" it were an agent, the quality of its uncertainty is transformed. Uncertainty about causal relations, which realistically can never be elucidated, is transformed into the other-worldly uncertainty of how the interaction partner will respond to Ego's actions. This puts Ego in the position to influence the further course of action by his own actions, to observe Alter's reactions and to draw consequences for his next action."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5c5303e6b9852b52",
      "text": "From another theoretical perspective, [[Daniel Dennett]] reaches a comparable conclusion with the idea of \"intentional stance\"; cf. Daniel Dennett (1987) The Intentional Stance, Cambridge, Mass.: MIT Press, 15 ff. However, while Dennett speaks only of the predictability of rational action, the notion of personification in the context of systems theory is oriented toward all human action, regardless of its rationality."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7b058177acc6562a",
      "text": "To adopt the intentional stance toward these monkeys is to decide – tentatively, of course – to attempt to characterize, predict, and explain their behavior by using intentional idioms, such as \"believes \" and \"wants,\" a practice that assumes or presupposes the rationality of the vervets. A vervet monkey is, we will say, an intentional system, a thing whose behavior is predictable by attributing beliefs and desires (and, of course, rationality) to it. (Daniel Clement Dennett, The intentional stance, p. 242.)"
