    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "2be95153b7285f18",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "2be95153b7285f18",
        "text": "Economists point to the reduction of transaction costs in multipolar economic relations, sociologists stress the coordination advantages of resource pools, while lawyers tend to emphasize the legal \"immortality\" of non-corporeal entities-the immortality of the church, the state, the corporation. Luhmann hypothesizes that once social systems are personified, they gain considerable advantages in their environmental positions. Latour sees personification as a secular opportunity to expand the pool of potential candidates who can actively participate in the political ecology. These are important insights, but I want to highlight another aspect. In encounters with nonhuman entities, their personification proves to be one of the most effective strategies for dealing with uncertainty. Personification transforms a subject-object relationship into an ego-alter relationship. To this extent, although it also does not generate certainty about age from Ego's point of view, it enables Ego to act in situations where age is opaque. When Ego treats an object \"as if\" it were an agent, the quality of its uncertainty is transformed. Uncertainty about causal relations, which realistically can never be elucidated, is transformed into the other-worldly uncertainty of how the interaction partner will respond to Ego's actions. This puts Ego in the position to influence the further course of action by his own actions, to observe Alter's reactions and to draw consequences for his next action."
      },
